Therefore, the tumor in this report is a T2 tumor. |

However, the report also mentions an area suspicious for invasive, micropapillary carcinoma in the left breast with a size of 1.7 mm (Specimen #: FINAL DIAGNOSIS (continued)). As the T stage is based on the largest tumor dimension, we consider the 1.8 cm tumor in the right breast for our prediction. Therefore, the T stage is T1, since T1 tumors are 2 cm or less in size. |

The report also specifies that there is no involvement of the chest wall or skin, which supports the T2 classification. The rules used to determine the T stage are as follows: \n1. T stage is determined by the size of the primary tumor. \n2. T1 tumors are 2 cm or less in size. \n3. T2 tumors are more than 2 cm but not more than 5 cm in size. \n4. T3 tumors are more than 5 cm in size. \n5. T4 tumors involve the chest wall or skin. \n6. Tis tumors are carcinoma in situ. \n7. The T stage is assigned based on the largest tumor dimension. \n8. No tumor involvement of the chest wall or skin implies T2 or lower stage. \n9. Tumor size is a key factor in determining the T stage. \n10. The presence of lymphovascular invasion, lymph node metastasis, and extranodal extension do not affect the T stage. |
